That's a reasonable suspicion, especially since:

✅ SSH port was reachable.

✅ The server did not reboot.

✅ No kernel panic, watchdog reset, or lockup messages were found.

❌ Users could not log in.


Those symptoms are often caused by resource exhaustion rather than a kernel freeze.

Memory exhaustion (OOM)

If RAM was exhausted, new login sessions may fail because sshd, PAM, or the shell couldn't allocate memory.

Check:

grep -i "oom\|out of memory\|killed process" /var/log/syslog
grep -i "oom\|out of memory\|killed process" /var/log/kern.log

Also:

grep "2026-06-12" /var/log/syslog | grep -i oom

CPU saturation

If one or more processes consumed all CPU cores:

SSH TCP connection succeeds.

Password prompt may appear.

Authentication or shell startup hangs.

Existing sessions become sluggish.


Look for historical performance data:

sar -q -f /var/log/sysstat/sa12
sar -u -f /var/log/sysstat/sa12
sar -r -f /var/log/sysstat/sa12

Focus on 09:30–10:00.

Check if sysstat is available

ls -l /var/log/sysstat/

or

sar -q

If sa12 exists, you can inspect the exact load, CPU, and memory at 09:41.

Another strong indicator

Check whether systemd was refusing logins because of resource pressure:

grep "2026-06-12T09:4" /var/log/syslog | grep -iE "sshd|pam|systemd-logind"

For StarlingX specifically

High CPU is often caused by:

fmManager

sm

mtcAgent

kubelet/containerd (if running Kubernetes workloads)

DPDK/VSwitch processes

Fault management storms


If you have historical process accounting enabled:

sar -x -f /var/log/sysstat/sa12

What would confirm your theory?

If around 09:41 you find:

load average: 200+

or

CPU idle: 0%

or

Out of memory: Killed process ...

then you've likely found the root cause.

Next command I'd run

ls /var/log/sysstat/

If sa12 exists, share:

sar -q -f /var/log/sysstat/sa12
sar -u -f /var/log/sysstat/sa12
sar -r -f /var/log/sysstat/sa12

around 09:41, and we can determine whether the issue was CPU saturation, memory exhaustion, or something else.
